    <summary>The context discusses various email exchanges between Bitcoin developers and open-source evangelists regarding the implementation of multisig wallets, HD wallets, and payment protocols. The discussion centers around multisig wallets and the development of HD (hierarchical deterministic) wallets. The Bitcoin community is working towards the adoption of HD wallets, which will likely lead to a significant migration away from random private keys. There are concerns about the complexity of setting up multisig wallets and the potential for malicious parties to steal funds. A BIP (Bitcoin Improvement Proposal) for a payment protocol using multisig has been suggested to aid future usability of multisig wallet implementations.Armory plans to introduce a wallet "bundle" that includes all wallets protected by the same backup and stored in the same file. They plan to allow separate parties to create multisig-intended wallets with public parts that can be exported and combined with other users. Meanwhile, Ciphrex CoinVault uses parallel trees with lexicographic sorting of keys and partially signed transaction format. There was a discussion on the implications of fees on the signing process of partially signed transactions in Bitcoind. Mike Hearn suggested calculating the size of a transaction in advance based on the initial transaction size and the number of required signatures. Raw transaction API in bitcoind does not take into account sig pushes that increase the fee level of partially signed and multisig transactions. Developers may need to implement a fee loop in their apps to avoid problems. Multisig outputs should be used as a tool to build helpful features such as multi-user money pools, dispute-mediated transactions, watchdog services, and micropayment channels. There is a need for multisig wallets to become more user-friendly and secure, and a BIP could help with this. The importance of planning and specifying the user experience for fully interoperable "mu